Oct 8 2007 	Great Value	We stayed in a deluxe room which was spacious. Besides a QS bed, which was firm and comfortable with comfortable pillows, there was a full size sofa and 3 easy chairs and 3 smallish tables. All the furniture was co-ordinated well and aesthetically pleasing. The lighting options in the room were excellent. The room had a TV, fridge and safe. The bathroom had a shower over the bath and plenty of hot water.The hotel is located in a moderately 'scruffy' street but is conveniently located near a supermarket and some convenience stores, fast food outlets and the train station and subway. However, taxis were so cheap and readily available we used them frequently. Dinner and breakfasts were nothing to get excited about but quite edible and value for money.We would stay there again and recommend it to our friends.	
Oct 3 2007 	Overall a good place to stay	The Hotel itself is ageing and needs renovation, but having said that the rooms were comfortable and were generally clean, so we had no complaints apart from the “air conditioning” whch just seemed to push air around no matter what temperature was selected. It wasn’t too much of a problem at this time of year but you couldn’t live with it in the Summer. There was a mini-mart across the road that sold cheap beer and wine should you want to buy some, and (if you’re not eating in the Hotel restaurant) there’s a restaurant behind the Hotel that we found to be fine (and cheap) and one of the waitresses spoke some English which helped. The Hotel staff seemed a bit tired so I guess they were working long hours, and getting service at the Hotel bar was almost impossible the night we tried as the bar person was working in the Hotel restaurant also. There’s a fair amount of construction going on around the area and I would guess that this Hotel will be either renovated or demolished at some stage in the next 2-3 years possibly, but there was no problems with construction noise. From here you could also walk to the shopping in Wangfujing Street for shopping	
Sep 15 2007	Convenient hotel if arriving in Beijing by train	Overall, the Harmony Hotel is reasonable value. This hotel seemed to be popular with western tourists. The location is great if you are travelling to/from Beijing by train. The Beijing Train Station (Beijing Zhan) is only 5 minutes walk. It is also located close enough to Wangfujing St (Shopping) - 15 minutes walk and Tiananmen Square/Forbidden City - 25 minutes walk. You can catch the subway from Beijing Zhan to Tiananmen Square for 6RMB (5 minutes duration, 2 stops).It is a noisy hotel, there are people coming and going at all hours. This is one of the pitfalls of being close to the train station. There was also a new building under construction close by which added to the noise. The room size is ok and the facilities were in good condition.The breakfast here was disappointing and provided limited choice. The restaurant is small and was packed every time I visited (different time each morning). There is a small supermarket across the road and other places around the corner on the way to the train station as alternatives for breakfast.The level of English spoken was ok throughout, as long as you don't have any unusual requests. There is a massage place next door and it's a bit dingy. Before going here, I suggest you know enough Mandarin to explain clearly what you want. A massage is not necessarily a massage in China. Get help from a local if you don't know Mandarin. If you request a foot massage, expect to be led down a corridor to a back room with about 20 recliners occupied by Chinese men in boxer shorts having a cigarette and watching TV. A taxi from Beijing Airport to this hotel is around 90RMB. As always in China, have the hotel details available in Chinese for the taxi driver. I caught many taxis in Beijing and not one taxi driver knew where this hotel was based on saying the name alone, even in Mandarin.	
