Apr 29 2007 	Convenient and Economical	I'm writing this review as I feel guilty that I have used the forum on multiple occasions but never contributed to it. This was our third hotel stay during our China trip. Our expectation for this hotel was low hoping that it would provide a clean and quiet room for sleeping as we are out the whole day and don't care for any extra amenities. We were not disappointed. The beds are very firm just like other hotels in China which is OK with us. We used the morning breakfast buffet serving the usual western and chinese fare for a reasonable price of 30RMB. The hotel is in a very convenient location for using public transportation to the airport, train station and the attractions in Beijing. Lot of cheap restaurants, fast food like Mcdonald, KFC etc and couple of 24 hr convenience stores around the area as it is across the train station. Could never get back to the hotel in time to have dinner but the menu seemed reasonable.The shower stall was small, about 3 sq ft, but what could be significant for some people is the fact that I had to go in side ways to fit thru the door which is about 1.5 ft and I weigh 150 pounds. The only hotel we stayed in where the water was really hot. House keeping was very good. Never turned the TV on.It is true that there is no good shopping around the area. If you are looking for knock off brandname merchandise there are two indoor shopping malls/markets which are easily accessible by taxi, bus or subway. Wagfujing area is a few subway stops away. Never had to spend more than 20RMB for taxi.We took the airport bus (exit door 11 once you clear immigration and customs and buy your ticket 16RMB and go to the bus stop #2 which is right across the ticket counter with the sign- Beijing Train station). Got off at the last stop after 1:15. The stop where you get off is a bit farther off than the stop you will get on to the bus to the airport). Walk about 5 minutes towards the train station (in the direction the bus is going/facing) upto the first cross walk. You will see the green hotel sign across the street to your left. You will pass the stop to go back to the airport just before you get to the cross walk. Obviously this will work if you can easily wheel your luggage as otherwise you may be at the mercy of the few taxi touts hanging around the bus stop.The Beijing Zhan Subway/Metro stop is just around the corner from the hotel across the train station and is a 5 min walk. 3RMB takes you any where on line 1 or 2 which is what you will need as of now but I'm not sure if this will change when the new lines open before the olympics. All signs and announcements (you actually hear them unlike chicago or New York trains) in chinese and english with very clear signs and maps. Felt very safe and secure unlike NY, Chicago, Spain or Italy.Plenty of buses if you know where they are going as the signs are in chinese and no one speaks english. Felt safe and secure but language was a problem.Single most useful thing we carried with us was a map with streets and attractions marked in english and chinese. You show the chinese script to almost any one and they point you in the right direction.I'll try to post on a different string about our other experiences including Beijing attractions, Shanghai and Suzhou as well as experiences with the people.	
